BCseafood_data <- read.csv("/Users/l/Downloads/compilation-of-2019-21-seafood-production-data-for-posting-in-bcdc-csv.csv")

BCseafood_data$Year <- as.numeric(as.character(BCseafood_data$Year))


Seafood_2021 <- BCseafood_data %>% 
  filter(Year == 2021)

print("The dataset captures information about seafood production in British Columbia, Canada, over the years 2019 to 2021. Key variables include the species or product type, source (wild commercial fisheries), the production year, harvested quantity (in thousand metric tons), landed value (in million CAD), and wholesale value of processed products (in million CAD). The dataset offers insights into the diverse seafood landscape in BC, covering a wde range of species and seafood sources.")

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

top_species_harvest_2021 <- Seafood_2021 %>%
  group_by(Species.Product) %>%
  summarise(Total_Harvest = sum(`Harvest...000.t.`), .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(desc(Total_Harvest))

top10_species_harvest_2021 <- top_species_harvest_2021[1:10,]

# Bar plot
ggplot(top10_species_harvest_2021, aes(x = reorder(Species.Product, -Total_Harvest), y = Total_Harvest)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Species by Annual Seafood Harvest in BC (2021)",
       x = "Species/Product", y = "Total Annual Seafood Harvest (000 t)") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = top10_species_harvest_2021$Species.Product)

print("Visualization 1: The bar plot illustrates the top 10 species by annual seafood harvest in BC. Among these species, 'Atlantic Salmon, Farmed' and 'Hake, Wild' displays as the dominant contributor to the total annual harvest. On the other hand, we can see that 'Sea Urchins Red, Wild' are more rare as they are the least harvested out of the top 10. The visualization reveals notable variability in harvest quantities,showcasing the diversity of seafood production in the region. Additionally, the economic contributions of these top-harvested species, emphasizes the importance of these marine resources to the BC's economy.")

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

top_species_wholesale <- Seafood_2021 %>%
  group_by(Species.Product) %>%
  summarise(Total_Wholesale_Value = sum(`Wholesale.Value....million.`), .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(desc(Total_Wholesale_Value))

top10_species_wholesale <- top_species_wholesale[1:10, ]

# Bar plot
ggplot(top10_species_wholesale, aes(x = reorder(Species.Product, -Total_Wholesale_Value), y = Total_Wholesale_Value)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "purple") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Species by Wholesale Value of Processed Products in BC 
       (2021)",
       x = "Species/Product", y = "Total Wholesale Value (million)") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = top10_species_wholesale$Species.Product)

print("Visualization 2: The visualization is a bar plot depicting the top 10 seafood species or products in British Columbia for 2021, based on their total wholesale values. Each bar represents a species, ordered by descending wholesale value. This visualization provides a concise overview of the most economically significant seafood products in terms of processed wholesale value. We can see that 'Atlantic Salmon, Farmed' and 'Crabs, Wild' contribute significantly to the overall economic value of the BC seafood industry, while 'Tuna, Wild' and 'Pacific Salomon, Farmed' are are the lower end and does not hold as much value but is still in the top 10 in BC's economy")
